text: Our fridge woes continue. It was super stinky when I arrived to the office this AM. Turns out the culprit was a bag of dead broccoli left in one of the door compartments. Got rid of it and opened some windows and doors.
Apologies to the owner of said broccoli bad for throwing it away. I'm pretty sure it was no longer edible (by mammals at least).

boeing and spacex were each awarded a contract, based on the same proposal requirements. Spacex got $2.6B, Boeing $4.2B. This cost is to cover certification (including 5 reviews and a NASA-manned crew flight demo), "special studies" and a third thing I couldn't write down in time.
through the commercial crew program, nasa will be able to rely on american companies to deliver and return astronauts to the ISS, as well as to conduct new deep-space missions.

bolden specifically mentioned a few mission milestones for the next few decades: first crew to visit and sample an asteroid, first crew to go beyond the moon, first crew to grow & eat food while in space (I think from the spaceship, not a terraformed planet/asteroid), first crew on mars.
